#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_design.rst:5
msgid "Designing a Part in build123d"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_design.rst:7
msgid ""
"Designing a part with build123d involves a systematic approach that "
"leverages the power of 2D profiles, extrusions, and revolutions. Where "
"possible, always work in the lowest possible dimension, 1D lines before 2D "
"sketches before 3D parts. The following guide will get you started:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_design.rst:12
msgid "*As an example, we'll go through the design process for this bracket:*"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_design.rst:19
msgid "Step 1. Examine the Part in All Three Orientations"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_design.rst:21
msgid ""
"Start by visualizing the part from the front, top, and side views. Identify "
"any symmetries in these orientations, as symmetries can simplify the design "
"by reducing the number of unique features you need to model."
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_design.rst:25
msgid ""
"*In the following view of the bracket one can see two planes of symmetry so "
"we'll only need to design one quarter of it.*"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_design.rst:32
msgid "Step 2. Identify Rotational Symmetries"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_design.rst:34
msgid ""
"Look for structures that could be created through the rotation of a 2D "
"shape. For instance, cylindrical or spherical features are often the result "
"of revolving a profile around an axis. Identify the axis of rotation and "
"make a note of it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_design.rst:38
msgid "*There are no rotational structures in the example bracket.*"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_design.rst:41
msgid "Step 3. Select a Convenient Origin"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_design.rst:43
msgid ""
"Choose an origin point that minimizes the need to move or transform "
"components later in the design process. Ideally, the origin should be placed"
" at a natural center of symmetry or a critical reference point on the part."
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_design.rst:47
msgid ""
"*The planes of symmetry for the bracket was identified in step 1, making it "
"logical to place the origin at the intersection of these planes on the "
"bracket's front face. Additionally, we'll define the coordinate system we'll"
" be working in: Plane.XY (the default), where the origin is set at the "
"global (0,0,0) position. In this system, the x-axis aligns with the front of"
" the bracket, and the z-axis corresponds to its width. It’s important to "
"note that all coordinate systems/planes in build123d adhere to the* `right-"
"hand rule <https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Right-hand_rule>`_ *meaning the "
"y-axis is automatically determined by this convention.*"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_design.rst:60
msgid "Step 4. Create 2D Profiles"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_design.rst:61
msgid ""
"Design the 2D profiles of your part in the appropriate orientation(s). These"
" profiles are the foundation of the part's geometry and can often represent "
"cross-sections of the part. Mirror parts of profiles across any axes of "
"symmetry identified earlier."
msgstr ""

