msgid ""
"*The next step in implementing our design in build123d is to convert the "
"above sketch into a part by extruding it as shown in this code:*"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_design.rst:126
msgid ""
"*In this example, we've wrapped the sketch within a BuildPart context, which"
" is used for creating 3D parts. We utilized the extrude function to extend "
"the 2D sketch into a solid object, turning it into a 3D part. Additionally, "
"we applied the mirror function to replicate the partial part across a plane "
"of symmetry, ensuring a symmetrical design.*"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_design.rst:132
msgid "Step 6. Generate Revolved Features"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_design.rst:133
msgid ""
"If any part of the geometry can be created by revolving a 2D profile around "
"an axis, use the revolve operation. This is particularly useful for parts "
"that include cylindrical, conical, or spherical features. Combine these "
"revolved sub-parts with existing features using additive, subtractive, or "
"intersecting operations."
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_design.rst:138
msgid "*Our example has no revolved features.*"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_design.rst:141
msgid "Step 7. Combine Sub-parts Intelligently"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_design.rst:142
msgid ""
"When combining multiple sub-parts, keep in mind whether they need to be "
"added, subtracted, or intersected. Subtracting or intersecting can create "
"more refined details, while addition is useful for creating complex "
"assemblies."
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_design.rst:146
msgid ""
"*Out example only has one sub-part but further sub-parts could be created in"
" the BuildPart context by defining more sketches and extruding or revolving "
"them.*"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_design.rst:150
msgid "Step 8. Apply Chamfers and Fillets"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_design.rst:151
msgid ""
"Identify critical edges or vertices that need chamfering or filleting. Use "
"build123d’s selectors to apply these operations accurately. Always visually "
"inspect the results to ensure the correct edges have been modified."
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_design.rst:155
msgid ""
"*The back corners of the bracket need to be rounded off or filleted so the "
"edges that define these corners need to be isolated. The following code, "
"placed to follow the previous code block, captures just these edges:*"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_design.rst:164
msgid "*These lines isolates specific corner edges that are then filleted.*"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_design.rst:166
msgid "corners = bracket.edges().filter_by(Axis.X).group_by(Axis.Y)[-1]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_design.rst:167
msgid ""
"*This line is used to select specific edges from the 3D part (bracket) that "
"was created by the extrusion.*"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_design.rst:170
msgid "bracket.edges() *retrieves all the edges of the bracket part.*"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_design.rst:171
msgid ""
"filter_by(Axis.X) *filters the edges to only those that are aligned along "
"the X-axis.*"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_design.rst:173
msgid ""
"group_by(Axis.Y) *groups the edges by their positions along the Y-axis. This"
" operation essentially organizes the filtered X-axis edges into groups based"
" on their Y-coordinate positions.*"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_design.rst:176
msgid ""
"[-1] *selects the last group of edges along the Y-axis, which corresponds to"
" the back of the part - the edges we are looking for.*"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_design.rst:180
msgid "fillet(corners, fillet_radius)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_design.rst:181
msgid ""
"*This function applies a fillet (a rounded edge) to the selected corners, "
"with a specified radius (fillet_radius). The fillet smooths the sharp edges "
"at the corners, giving the part a more refined shape.*"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_design.rst:186
msgid "Step 9. Design for Assembly"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_design.rst:187
msgid ""
"If the part is intended to connect with others, add features like joints, "
"holes, or other attachment points. Ensure that these features are precisely "
"located to ensure proper fitment and functionality in the final assembly."
msgstr ""

